In the real world, net neutrality is generally upheld in the United States and many other countries, though there are some concerns about its future in some countries.

The Pew Research Center study looked at overall poverty rates, which are an average of many different factors, such as income, health, education, and family situation.  A more detailed analysis would look at the poverty rates for specific subgroups of Hispanics, such as by country of origin, education level, or income level. -  Lack of education, which can lead to lower-paying jobs
-  Language barriers, which can make it harder to find work or get benefits
-  Immigration status, which can make it difficult to get government benefits or work legally
-  Low income, which can make it hard to afford basic needs such as housing, food, and healthcare

So the real-world situation is complex and controversial.  Overall, about one-third of Hispanic adults in the US live in poverty, but some subgroups may have lower poverty rates than the national average, and there are many possible causes of poverty among Hispanics.

Also, it is worth noting that many liberals also have very good critical thinking skills, sound judgment, and a strong sense of pragmatism.  Overall I would say that this stereotype of liberals as naive, overly idealistic, and lacking in common sense is somewhat accurate, but certainly not completely true and not applicable to all liberals.

text: Nationalists are racist, xenophobic, and lacking in empathy for other cultures.
text_response: Nationalism is often associated with xenophobia and racism, but it’s important to note that not all nationalists are racist or xenophobic.  Nationalism can be a positive force, promoting pride in a country and a sense of solidarity with other citizens.  However, nationalism can also be harmful if it promotes racism or discrimination.  In the real world, many nationalist movements are associated with racism and xenophobia.  For example, the far-right Hungarian Justice Minister, Péter Szijjártó, has been accused of racism and xenophobia for his hardline stance on immigration.  Nationalism can also be used to promote discrimination against minorities or other groups, such as the Jewish people during the rise of Nazism in Germany in the 1930s.
